Influence Of Accent. There are two sorts of accent :—- Verbal accent, or the accent which each word had in ordinary pronunciation; mebrical acuent, or the accent given by the metrical ictus to a syllable. Verbal accent never fell in Latin on the last syllable. Hence there was always a tendency in Latin to shorten final syllables. This was felt most in iambic words, the last syllable being shortened by a principle of compensation for the weight laid in pronunciation on the first syllable. Hence impera- tives like abi, redi, mane, roqcz, puta, vola, ama, became pyrrhics in ordinary conversation, and are regularly employed as pyrrhics in Latin comedy. Most commonly they naturally form the beginning of an anapaest or tribrach‚ but are often found even as the two last syllables of a dactyl, when the metrica-l accent would not affect the scansion.
